<img class="alignnone wp-image-1260230" src="https://i1.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/inec-3.jpg?resize=500%2C264&#038;ssl=1" alt="Bayelsa,Kogi polls: IHRC urges security agencies, INEC to address security, logistics concerns" width="500" height="264" srcset="https://i1.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/inec-3.jpg?w=800&amp;ssl=1 800w, https://i1.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/inec-3.jpg?resize=300%2C159&amp;ssl=1 300w, https://i1.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/inec-3.jpg?resize=768%2C406&amp;ssl=1 768w, https://i1.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/inec-3.jpg?resize=58%2C31&amp;ssl=1 58w, https://i1.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/inec-3.jpg?resize=260%2C137&amp;ssl=1 260w, https://i1.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/inec-3.jpg?resize=200%2C106&amp;ssl=1 200w, https://i1.wp.com/www.vanguardngr.com/wp-content/uploads/2019/09/inec-3.jpg?resize=560%2C296&amp;ssl=1 560w" sizes="(max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px" data-recalc-dims="1" /> The International Human Rights Commission, IHRC, has appealed to security agencies and the Independent National Electoral Commission, INEC, to immediately address the security and logistics concerns arising from Saturday’s governorship elections in Bayelsa and Kogi states. The international rights organisation, which said it has established command centres in the two states for the purpose of observing the elections, also asked governors of both states to “show concern for their citizens during the elections so that the outcome can be acceptable to all concerned.” In a press statement, Thursday evening, the organisation through its spokesman, Dr. Kenneth Anozie, said it observed that “they have been reported cases of violence during the electioneering in these two states, but with particular reference to Kogi State where some security agencies have been indicted for partisanship.” The statement read thus:”The International Human Rights Commission, Geneva, (United Nations Affiliate) Nigeria Committee has called on the Nigeria Security Agencies and the Independent National Electoral Commission, INEC, to immediately address the concerns raised by the electorates, Monitoring and Observer Agencies, and opposition parties in the two states where election is to be conducted on Saturday, 16th November 2019. “The IHRC observe that they have been reported cases of violence during the electioneering in these two states, but with particular reference to Kogi State where some security Agencies have been indicted for partisanship. “As one of the Agencies with observer status in the upcoming election, we have deployed a lot of our personnel across the State concern and set up a command center from where we can monitor happenings across all the electoral wards in the state. “We urge the incumbent Governors to show concern for their citizens during the elections so that the outcome can be acceptable to all concerned. ” vanguard The Centre for Transparency and Advocacy (CTA) has called for synergy between the police, political parties as well as the Independent National Electoral Commission (INEC) to ensure that the November governorship election in Kogi, and Bayelsa states is free and credible. July 30, 2019 In "News" THE Independent National Electoral Commission, INEC, has expressed commitment to the conduct of Saturday’s governorship election in Kogi and Bayelsa states, assuring stakeholders that in spite of several post-election court cases in both states, no last-minute judicial pronouncement could alter the elections. November 13, 2019 In "Politics" Election observer group, Centre for Transparency Advocacy (CTA) has said it is concerned with the high rate of violence ahead of the November 16 Kogi and Bayelsa governorship elections October 24, 2019 In "News"